TI  - Carbon Adsorbents Obtained from Pistachio Nut Shells Used as Potential Ingredients of Drinking Water Filters
AU  - Agata Wawrzyniak
AU  - Małgorzata Wiśniewska
AU  - Piotr Nowicki
PY  - 2023
DO  - 10.3390/molecules28114497
UR  - https://www.mdpi.com/1420-3049/28/11/4497
AB  - Water resources are increasingly degraded due to the discharge of waste generated in municipal, industrial and agricultural areas. Therefore, the search for new materials enabling the effective treatment of drinking water and sewage is currently of great interest. This paper deals with the adsorption of organic and inorganic pollutants on the surface of carbonaceous adsorbents prepared by thermochemical conversion of common pistachio nut shells. The influence of the direct physical activation with CO 2 and chemical activation with H 3 PO 4 on parameters, such as elemental composition, textural parameters, acidic–basic character of the surface as well as electrokinetic properties of the prepared carbonaceous materials was checked. The suitability of the activated biocarbons prepared as the adsorbents of iodine, methylene blue and poly(acrylic acid) from the aqueous solutions was estimated. The sample obtained via chemical activation of the precursor turned out to be much more effective in terms of all the tested pollutants adsorption. Its maximum sorption capacity toward iodine was 1059 mg/g, whereas in relation to methylene blue and poly(acrylic acid) 183.1 mg/g and 207.9 mg/g was achieved, respectively. For both carbonaceous materials, a better fit to the experimental data was achieved with a Langmuir isotherm than a Freundlich one. It has also been shown that the efficiency of organic dye, and especially anionic polymer adsorption from aqueous solutions, is significantly affected by solution pH and temperature of the adsorbate–adsorbent system.
ER  - 

TY  - JOUR
TI  - A comprehensive data-driven approach for robust investigation of viscosity of nano-polymer composites utilized as enhanced oil recovery agents
AU  - Mohammad Madani
AU  - Mahdi Abbasi
PY  - 2026
DO  - 10.1016/j.matdes.2026.115741
UR  - http://www.sciencedirect.com/science/article/pii/S026412752600314X
AB  - The viscosity of nano–polymer composites used in enhanced oil recovery (EOR) is governed by complex and highly nonlinear interactions that limit the applicability of conventional predictive correlations. To address this challenge, this study develops robust data-driven models based on a comprehensive dataset of 1447 experimental points. The dataset spans temperatures from 25 to 90 °C, polymer concentrations of 0.1–15 wt%, nanoparticle concentrations of 0.1–1 wt%, and shear rates between 9.75 and 1021.38 s−1. Input parameters include temperature, polymer and nanoparticle concentrations, shear rate, and the types of polymers (guar gum, gum arabic, xanthan gum) and nanoparticles (alumina, copper, silica). In addition to viscosity enhancement, nanoparticle incorporation is motivated by their role as sacrificial agents that can reduce polymer adsorption onto rock surfaces and modify wettability in porous media, thereby influencing the effective rheological behavior of polymer solutions in EOR processes. The viscosity values ranged from 1.30 to 2160 cP. The dataset explicitly includes polymer systems both in the absence and presence of nanoparticles, enabling the models to capture viscosity variations before and after nanoparticle incorporation. The results demonstrate that nanoparticle addition generally enhances viscosity through particle–polymer interactions, although the magnitude of this enhancement is strongly dependent on shear rate, polymer concentration, and nanoparticle type. Multiple machine learning models were utilized, including Decision Tree, Random Forest, Adaptive Boosting (AdaBoost), K-Nearest Neighbors (KNN), Convolutional Neural Networks (CNN), and Ensemble Learning. SHAP analysis recognized shear rate as primary element affecting viscosity, while nanoparticle type had the least impact. A correlation-based sensitivity analysis was used to verify well-established rheological trends, including the direct influence of polymer and nanoparticle concentrations and the inverse influence of shear rate and temperature on viscosity. The Leverage method was used to assess data quality, identifying 18 outliers, though all points were retained for modeling. Models were trained and validated using 5-fold cross-validation. AdaBoost (50 estimators) and Random Forest (depth 9) outperformed others, with R2 values of 0.999254 and 0.998399, and low MSE and AARE% values. CNN showed the weakest performance. Ensemble Learning further improved accuracy (R2 = 0.999191, MSE = 74.49). Cross-plots and error distribution analyses confirmed the reliability and robustness of the top models. These findings demonstrate that ensemble learning methods especially AdaBoost and Random Forest offer high accuracy and scalability for predicting viscosity in EOR systems. The developed models provide efficient screening and decision-support capabilities for viscosity estimation and nano–polymer composite optimization under laboratory-scale conditions relevant to enhanced oil recovery applications.
ER  - 

