PY  - 2025
DO  - 10.1016/j.matdes.2025.114666
UR  - http://www.sciencedirect.com/science/article/pii/S026412752501086X
AB  - Removal of emerging antibiotic is of great importance because antibiotic resistance is serious problem for human health. Novel adsorbents are atttracted intense study but very few study has been investigated the performance of different phase structures of adsorbent with surface modification by polymer. This study investigated the adsorption characteristics of the antibiotic levofloxacin (LFX) on α-Al2O3 and γ-Al2O3 nanoparticles modified with poly (2-acrylamide-2-methylpropane sulfonic acid) (PAMPs) and poly (3-sulfopropyl acrylate potassium) (PAPS). Surface modifications of α-Al2O3 and γ-Al2O3 by the adsorption of two polyanions significantly enhanced LFX removal efficiencies. Zeta potential measurements revealed that the surface charge of α-Al2O3 reversed from positive to highly negative after modification with PAMPs, while γ-Al2O3 underwent a similar charge reversal after modification with PAPS. Fourier-transform infrared spectroscopy confirmed the appearance of key functional groups C=O and N-H in PAMPs, and C=O and C-O in PAPS, indicating successful polymer adsorption on the nano-Al2O3 surface. The optimal conditions for LFX removal using 20 mg/mL PAMPs modified α-Al2O3 and 10 mg/mL PAPS modified γ-Al2O3 were found to be pH 7, adsorption time 90 min and pH 8, adsorption time 120 min, respectively. Adsorption isotherms followed a two-step adsorption process, while adsorption kinetics were best described by the pseudo-second-order model. Both modified adsorbents achieved the LFX removal efficiencies exceeding 85 %, with maximum adsorption capacities of greater than 20 mg/g, values significantly higher than many other adsorbents. Furthermore, the modified adsorbents demonstrated high removal efficiencies of LFX in actual water samples, achieving recoveries of greater than 80 %. These findings highlight the potential of polymer-modified α-Al2O3 and γ-Al2O3 nanoparticles as high-performance materials for antibiotic removal.
